title: SpeedWorks Leadville Altitude Training Camp
description: If you are looking to do well at Leadville or the Breck Epic, let SpeedWorks help you fine tune your training, and give you an edge going into the race.  This is a 5-day Altitude Mountain Bike Training Camp run by SpeedWorks Coaching Group, LLC.  This camp will be a high volume altitude training camp aimed at preparation for the Leadville 100 Mtb race, or any other Mtb Endurance Race.  There will be a field limit of 10 athletes, and we will have a staff of 3 USA Cycling Licensed Coaches.  Included in the registration fee is group lodging in a cabin in Granby, CO for the nights of July 13-16 (4 nights).  Additional lodging nights are available for the 12th and/or the 17th.  In addition to the great training and lodging, SpeedWorks has brought in Licensed Dietician, and Owner of Fischer Nutrition to prepare all main meals between Lunch on the 13th and Lunch on the 17th.  The SpeedWorks Coaches will be holding discussions and educational presentations at least 3 of the 4 nights.  In addition to the volume training, there will also be several skills sessions, helping each athlete hone their skills and master their bike handling.  Attending this camp will help you determine how you handle the altitude, and will help prepare you for the demands of the Leadville Trail 100 Mtb Race in August.  The timing of this camp is perfect for setting you up for success!
course: The mountains, trails and dirt roads in and around Granby, Colorado.  Elevation will range from about 8500 - over 10,000 ft.
notes: This is a 5 day altitude training camp.
directions: After registering, you will receive several emails with details about the camp and location.

Route:
Loop 1
Starting in Telluride we will do a neutral roll out to the Idarado Mill East of town on Colorado Ave. 
Up/over Black Bear Pass to Hwy 550.
South on 550 to Ophir Pass (FR 679)
Right on FR 679 up/over Ophir Pass
Cross CO 145 to 625 Rd. and continue North.
Just before the intersection of 63J Rd., take a right onto the old Galloping Goose trail and proceed to the Lawson Hill area.
Once in Lawson Hill, take the hike/bike trail back to the Coonskin Lift (Chair 7) area.

Loop 2
From the St. Sophia Gondola Station take the Prospect Trail to Boomerang Rd. 
Boomerang Rd. to Alta Ghost Town.

Left on 145 and pass the intersection for 625 Rd.  About 100 meters after that, take a right on the Galloping Goose trail

title: Bob Cook Memorial Mt. Evans Hill Climb
description:
The Mt. Evans Hill climb is an iconic bicycle race that takes place on Mount Evans, Colorado. It was run for the first time in 1962. It was renamed in 1981 in honor of five-time race winner Bob Cook, who died of cancer at the age of 23. The climb is 27.4 miles in length and takes place on the highest paved road in the United States. It starts at an altitude of 7,540 feet and proceeds to Echo Lake where the race turns and climbs nearly to the summit at 14,130 feet

Over the years, the race has attracted significant professional riders. Riders come from all over the United States and in the past the race has had riders from France, Switzerland, Germany, and Australia compete. The age range of the participants is from 9 to 85 years of age. The event includes categories for all levels of racing and encourages riders of all abilities.

The present record holder is Tom Danielson, set in 2004 with a time of 1:41:20. The Senior Women's course record is held by Jeannie Longo from France with a time of 1:59.19
course:
The start point in Idaho Springs is about 45 minutes east of Summit County, but if you fancy yourself a climber, this is one of the "Big Kahunas" of Hill Climb. It's a 7,000' of climb from an elevation of 7,500' all the way up to 14,100.' For sure, climbing between 12,000' and 14,000' is a lot different than climbing from 10,000' to 12,000'.

The climb has a short flat at Echo Lake and a slight downhill just before Summit Lake. Grades to Echo Lake average 3.5% for 6.7 miles and 5.8% for 5.8 miles. Echo Lake to the summit averages 5.6% for 5.5 miles, then 4.1% for 2.7 miles and finally 5.7% for 4.25 miles to the top. Maximum grade is 10%.

There are 11 switchbacks that you can view from the top

title: Steamboat Stinger
description:
This year we are proud to announce the fourth annual, Steamboat Stinger. The Steamboat Stinger, now a Colorado classic, aims to provide a challenging backcountry race experience showcasing some of Steamboat Springs' finest singletrack. Like in years past, The Steamboat Stinger is also a fundraiser for Partners in Routt County (Local Youth Mentoring Group) and Routt County Riders (Local IMBA Chapter).
 
Just like in years past, in addition to the mountain bike race, we will also feature a full and half trail marathon as well. These two events can be separate, or if you wish to take the ultimate challenge, you can particiapte in both events- the 50 mile solo mountain bike race, and then the 26.2 trail marathing the next day - to be crowned King Sting or Queen Bee of the Steamboat Stinger.
 
These events are true to Steamboat Springs' tradition: epic fun with an added bit of western flair. Giddy up!
course:
THE MTB COURSE:
You can expect singletrack…lots of it. Beginning at the Howelson Hill Ski Area right in the heart of Steamboat, the course takes an extended detour deep into the beautiful backcountry of Routt County before returning to the transition/finish area. Racers will wind through open meadows, deeply-cupped, aspen-lined, narrow Colorado loam and wild sage gardens offering incredible views of the surrounding peaks and valleys. It's a 50-mile race, plus or minus a bit, composed of two 25-mile loops - 100% of which are on dirt featuring 90% singletrack. Full course info coming soon.

title: Monarch Crest Crank
description:
The Monarch Crest Crank is the historic fundraiser for the Chaffee County Alliance Against Domestic Abuse (AADA) and 2014 will be the best year yet.  The Crest Crank will be the final day of Salida Bike Fest week which includes days of fun for cyclists of all abilities and their families. This is the Crest Crank’s 16th year and AADA will continue to offer mountain bikers the chance to ride the famed Monarch Crest Trail, as it has since 1998.

Entry remains $75, plus pledges, for the Monarch Crest Trail ride.  On top of this bargain price, we highly encourage you to raise at least the same amount in personal pledges and sponsorships. We also have a sweet Silent Auction after the ride at the Riverside Park Party.

Your entry fee for the adult rides includes the ride, guide, shuttle and of course, our legendary party in Riverside Park after the ride. The top fundraiser bringing in more than $500 of pledges wins a stylish new cruiser bike.

Come join us in the fun and help raise funds to support the important work of AADA. This year the Monarch Crest Trail ride will be on Sunday, September 14, 2014!
course:
Known as one of the Top Ten Mountain Bike Rides in America, the Monarch Crest Trail is definitely one of the best rides you will ever do.  The ride starts on top of Monarch Pass at a lofty 11,312 feet and quickly climbs to the Continental Divide.  The singletrack follows the Divide for 10 miles above treeline through rock gardens and fields of wildflowers, climbs steep hills and drops back into thick pine forests.


Mountain Biking the Continental Divide – 2011 Crest Crank!
It’s pure singletrack and so fun.  On clear days, you can see all the way from Pikes Peak to the San Juan Mountains – the entire width of the Colorado Rockies.

After riding the Monarch Crest Trail, you have a choice of either riding down the challenging Silver Creek singletrack or choosing an easier route down the smooth dirt road of Marshall Pass.

Silver Creek is a fantastic, fun and rough skinny trail with some rocky challenges.  Marshall Pass is non-technical, an old Otto Mears railroad route that lets a mountain biker look up and enjoy the amazing Colorado Rocky Mountain scenery all around.

Logistics:
You must have your mountain bike ready to load on the shuttle on arrival – no last minute repairs or bike checks.

On Sept 15th, be at Salida Bike Company at  7:45am – 8:00am if you have already registered, earlier if not.  Shuttles leave at 8:30am sharp. Salida Bike Company is in downtown Salida (148 North F Street), we will load our bikes into the shuttle buses and drive to the summit of Monarch Pass for an early start.  Here we will start the faster riders and guides first and the slower riders second.

Faster riders can complete the ride in 3-4 hours.  Slower riders will need 5 hours.  The ride will officially end at the Shirley Site trailhead where shuttle buses will drive us back to Historic Downtown Salida for a great party in Riverside Park.

(Riders may choose to continue past Shirley Site and ride back to Salida, but this is where the Monarch Crest Crank officially ends, so you are on your own and not covered by event insurance past this point.  The ride from Shirley Site to Salida is an additional 13 miles.)

Details:
Distance: Approximately 25 High Altitude Miles
Aerobic Level: Strenuous
Technical Difficulty: Advanced – side slopes, rocky and loose
High Point: 11,989 Feet Above Sea Level
